          Unless you're a snob, a good Monkees collection belongs on your shelves, not too far 
          from discs by the Turtles, the Lovin' Spoonful, and other avatars of clean,          
          occasionally rocking '60s Top 40 pop. Greatest Hits is a more than generous stack,   
          bringing together not only the obvious megahits ("I'm a Believer," "Pleasant Valley  
          Sunday," the incredibly propulsive "Valleri") but also a number of tunes that had the
          bad luck to fall on the wrong side of the act's swift rise and fall. Foremost among  
          these is "Porpoise Song," a lyrically incomprehensible Goffin/King stab at           
          psychedelia that's at once a crass cashin and one of the loveliest, most fragile    
          sounds to emerge from the American hippie dream.
